<h3>Materials on the Web</h3>

<p>First of all, be wise in the use of PowerPoint or other
presentation software (I use
<a href="http://latex-beamer.sf.net">Beamer</a> and
<a href="http://sf.net/projects/pgf">PGF/TikZ</a> personally). Resist the
temptation to write too much on your slides: I don't want to suffer
death by bullet!</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://scienceblogs.com/principles/2006/11/how_to_do_a_good_powerpoint_le.php">How to do a Good PowerPoint Lecture</a>, by Chad Orzel.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/powerpoint">The Cognitive Style of
PowerPoint: Pitching Out Corrupts Within</a>, by Edward R. Tufte. (I have a
version of the first edition of this essay; come see me if you want to read it!)</li>
<li><a href="/good-talks-per-plam/">My opinions on what constitutes a good talk.</a>
<li>Jeff Offutt's thoughts on <a href="http://cs.gmu.edu/~offutt/classes/phd/Hints-Read.html">reading papers</a>.
</ul>

<p>You may also wish to refer to these notes on static analysis and Soot.
Please let me know if you find any other resources that I should list on
this page.</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.brics.dk/~mis/static.pdf">Notes on Static Analysis</a>, by Anders M&oslash;ller and Michael I. Schwartzbach.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.brics.dk/SootGuide">A Survivor's Guide to Java Program Analysis with Soot</a>, by Arni Einarsson and
Janus Dam Nielsen.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.sable.mcgill.ca/soot/tutorial/pldi03/tutorial.pdf">
PLDI 2003 Soot tutorial</a>, by Laurie Hndren, Patrick Lam, Jennifer Lhotak,
Ondrej Lhotak, and Feng Qian.
<li><a href="http://www.sable.mcgill.ca/soot/tutorial/">Other Soot Documentation</a>.
</ul>

<h3>Books</h3>

<p>Even though there is a lot of information on the Internet, there is even
more information in books. These books can give you another perspective on
the course material.</p>

<ul>
<li><i>Principles of Program Analysis</i>, by Flemming Nielson, Hanne Riis Nielson,
and Chris Hankin.</li>
<li><i>Advanced Compiler Design and Implementation</i>, by Steven Muchnick.</li>
<li><i>Compilers: Principles, Techniques and Tools</i> (2nd edition), by Alfred V.
Aho, Monica S. Lam (no relation), Ravi Sethi, and Jeffrey D. Ullman.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Past Projects</h3>

<p>To get an idea of the expected scope of a course project, see <a href="files/thiago-final-project.pdf">Verification of Object Collaborations with Tracechecks</a>, posted with the kind permission of Thiago Tonelli Bartolomei.</p>
